matchdetail.toss_summary: South Africa won the toss and elected to bowl.

comments.text: Over 39. 4 runs. Bowler: Lakshan Sandakan. South Africa: 2-232(rr 5.95)

Lakshan Sandakan to Faf du Plessis. Left-Arm Leg Spin length ball, off stump on the front foot working, to square leg for 1 run, fielded by Perera.  South Africa have completed a commanding victory in the First ODI against Sri Lanka in Johannesburg, cruising to their target just two wickets down and with lots of overs left in the bank. The total of 231 all out made by the tourists never looked like it was going to be enough and a serene partnership of 136 between Quinton de Kock and Faf du Plessis made sure of that fact. The South African skipper went on to make an unbeaten 112, his eleventh ODI century, as The Wanderers cheered him on in the afternoon sunshine. Sri Lanka made the mistake of dropping him early on and that sucked the energy from their performance, with the bowlers and fielders all looking fairly flat. Earlier in the day, Imran Tahir was excellent with the ball on a dry surface - his spell of 26-3 was as parsimonious as it was threatening. Sri Lanka contributed to their own downfall with the bat with soft dismissals costing them dearly, although Oshada Fernando played some eye-catching strokes on debut before Kusal Mendis' half century. They will need to improve on that in the Second ODI on Wednesday which takes place at Centurion.

APPEAL! Verified by umpire after REFERRAL. Imran Tahir to Isuru Udana. Googly length ball, outside off stump on the front foot defending, hit pad to wicketkeeper for no runs, by de Kock, appeal made for Caught.  In fairly bizarre circumstances we have a review. Tahir is so desperate for wickets, he is willing this to be out but umpire Kettleborough rarely gets decisions wrong. No inside edge and missing leg stump, Udana survives but the result is still the same. 

 South Africa have sealed victory in their ODI series against Sri Lanka by going 3-0 up thanks to a pretty sedate finish in front of an empty stadium at Kingsmead. The tourists were struggling in their run chase before the Durban rain intervened and all but ended their hopes, as by the time more play was possible the equation was reduced to 118 runs needed from eight overs. The Proteas were put in a dominant position earlier in the day by a majestic Quinton de Kock century, his supreme form continues in the build up to the World Cup. We'll be back on Wednesday for the Fourth ODI in Port Elizabeth.

South Africa have cruised to a six wicket victory in Port Elizabeth putting them on the brink of a whitewash against Sri Lanka in the five match ODI series. Quinton de Kock continued his spectacular form with yet another fluent half century at the top of the order, meaning the rest of the middle order could play without pressure as they eased to the target with more than 17 overs to spare. The tourists never looked like getting on top in this match, losing wickets in clusters earlier this morning at St George's Park as Anrich Nortje claimed 57-3. Only Isuru Udana offered any real resistance, spanking an outrageous 78 from just 57 deliveries to delay the inevitable loss. The final match of the series will be played in Cape Town on Saturday, before attention turns to the shortest format.

Test stars James Pattinson and Peter Siddle have ripped through the New South Wales batsmen this morning to lead Victoria to a 63 run win at Drummoyne Oval. Chasing 166 for victory, NSW were demolished by some hostile bowling from Pattinson who finished with 5-25. Siddle bowled his usual probing line and length and with some assistance from the overhead conditions, took the important wicket of Hughes to get the ball rolling for the visitors. A spirited last wicket partnership of 48 between Nevill and O'Keefe ensured NSW avoided their lowest ever Shield score against Victoria but it was the visitors day who wrapped up a highly entertaining and bowler-friendly match midway through the second session. 
This victory has all but assured Victoria of hosting the final, while NSW will still need to win their last match against Tasmania to ensure they will be their opponents
